This paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of cs.DB (Databases) as it deals with frequent episode discovery in temporal data mining, which is a common problem in database systems. It could also belong to cs.LG (Machine Learning) as the paper presents a unified view of different algorithms for episode discovery, which is a common problem in machine learning. Additionally, the paper discusses quantitative relationships among different frequencies, which is a common topic in data science and statistics, making cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) another likely sub-category. The paper also presents a generic algorithm that can be used to discover episodes with general partial orders, which is a common problem in artificial intelligence, making cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses correctness proofs for various algorithms, which is a common topic in cryptography, making cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) another possible sub-category.
